Truce License
==============

Copyright (c) 2025-2026 truce contributors

The truce framework (the "Software") is dual-licensed. Your rights
depend on the kind of product you ship.

  - **For plug-in authors and end-user audio software:**
    Apache License, Version 2.0, full text in LICENSE-APACHE.
    No additional restrictions, no fees, no attribution beyond what
    Apache 2.0 already requires. Most uses fall here.

  - **For free, OSI-licensed framework / SDK / developer-tool
    projects built on top of truce:** also Apache License,
    Version 2.0. The Section 2.1 exemption below restores the
    Apache grant for non-commercial Framework Products that
    publish their full source under an OSI-approved license and
    are not part of a Commercial Offering. No separate permission
    is required.

  - **For commercial audio-plug-in frameworks built on truce:**
    A separate Framework License is required, granted only by
    written permission from the Licensor. See Section 2 below;
    the request procedure is in Section 2.2.

Read on for the precise boundary.


1.  Author License — Apache 2.0
-------------------------------

If your use of the Software falls outside the Framework License
carve-out in Section 2, your rights under this Agreement are governed
in full by the **Apache License, Version 2.0** (the "Apache License"),
the text of which is reproduced in the file LICENSE-APACHE in this
repository and also available at:

  https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0

This includes — and is not limited to — building, modifying,
selling, and redistributing the Software as part of:

  - audio plug-ins conforming to CLAP, VST3, VST2, LV2, AU v2, AU v3,
    AAX, or successor specifications;
  - standalone audio applications, plug-in suites, host applications,
    analyzers, validators, tuners, metering tools;
  - hardware-vendor SDKs and runtimes that embed the Software as an
    internal implementation detail (not exposed as part of a
    developer-facing surface);
  - personal-use scripting, prototyping, and research code;
  - wrapper or helper libraries targeting a specific DSP technique,
    GUI backend, or external dependency.

Under the Apache License, your product may be commercial or
non-commercial, open-source or closed-source. No royalty, splash
screen, revenue cap, headcount cap, or registration is required. You
get Apache 2.0's patent grant and patent retaliation protections.

This is the only license you need for the use cases above. Most
plug-in authors stop reading here.


2.  Framework Products — Permission Required for Commercial Use
----------------------------------------------------------------

This Section applies only to **commercial** Framework Products.
Free, OSI-licensed, non-commercial Framework Products are covered
by the Section 2.1 exemption below and need no permission from the
Licensor — they receive the full Apache License grant from
Section 1.

For commercial Framework Products: the Apache License grant in
Section 1 does **not** extend to use of the Software in or as a
Framework Product that is also a Commercial Offering (as defined
in Section 2.1). A separate Framework License, granted only by
written permission from the Licensor, is required for that use.

A product is a "Framework Product" if both:

  (i)  it is offered, distributed, sublicensed, or otherwise provided
       to third-party developers as a means of building audio plug-ins
       (as enumerated in Section 1) or DAW host integrations; and

  (ii) the third-party developer's use of the product results in
       audio software that the third-party developer distributes to
       end users or to further developers.

The following are **not** Framework Products, and their distribution
is fully covered by the Apache License grant in Section 1:

  - any audio plug-in, plug-in suite, host, analyzer, validator,
    end-user audio application, or hardware product;
  - any hardware-vendor SDK or runtime that includes the Software
    as an internal implementation detail and does not expose the
    Software as part of its public developer interface;
  - any personal-use scripting layer, prototyping kit, or research
    library;
  - any wrapper or helper library targeting a specific DSP technique,
    GUI backend, or external dependency, even if useful to other
    plug-in authors as a transitive dependency.


2.1  Exemption — Free, Open-Source Framework Products
-----------------------------------------------------

The permission requirement in Section 2 does **not** apply to a
Framework Product that simultaneously satisfies all of the
following conditions for the entire period of its distribution:

  (a) The Framework Product's complete source code is published
      and made freely accessible under an OSI-approved open-source
      license. "OSI-approved" means a license appearing on the
      Open Source Initiative's approved-licenses list at
      https://opensource.org/licenses at the time of distribution.

  (b) The Framework Product is offered to its third-party
      developer users free of charge. Receiving voluntary
      donations, patronage (e.g. GitHub Sponsors, Open
      Collective, Patreon), or research / hobbyist grants for
      the Framework Product is permitted under this exemption
      provided no contributor receives those funds as
      consideration for use of the Framework Product.

  (c) The Framework Product is not a Commercial Offering.

A "Commercial Offering" means any product, service, or
arrangement that:

  (i)   requires payment, subscription, license fee, royalty,
        or other monetary consideration for access to, use of,
        modification of, or distribution of the Framework
        Product or its functionality;

  (ii)  is dual-licensed by its publisher under commercial terms
        in parallel with the open-source license referenced in
        (a) above;

  (iii) is bundled with, or used to gate access to, a paid
        product, paid support contract, paid hosting service,
        paid training, paid certification, or paid consulting
        offering where the Framework Product itself (rather than
        the paying customer's own audio software produced with
        the Framework Product) is the primary value being sold;
        or

  (iv)  is offered to the public under any other arrangement
        whose principal purpose is commercial advantage or
        monetary compensation to the Framework Product's
        publisher.

Framework Products meeting (a)–(c) are licensed under the Apache
License grant in Section 1 — no separate permission required.
Authors of such Framework Products are encouraged (but not
required) to notify the Licensor and may be listed in the
project's ecosystem documentation.

If a Framework Product subsequently becomes a Commercial
Offering, the exemption ceases to apply from the date the
Commercial Offering begins. Continued distribution of the
Framework Product from that date requires a written Framework
License under Section 2. Audio software already built with the
Framework Product under the prior exemption is unaffected.

The Licensor reserves the right to maintain a public list of
Commercial Offerings the Licensor has determined to fall outside
this exemption. Inclusion on or omission from such a list does
not by itself extend or revoke the exemption — the license
itself is the operative source of truth.


2.2  Framework License Grants (Commercial)
------------------------------------------

The Licensor is under no obligation to grant a Framework License.
When granted, the Licensor may impose any terms (including but not
limited to attribution, contribution-back, scope limits, financial
terms, revocation conditions, and time limits) as a condition of the
grant. Past grants do not bind future decisions.

Requests for a Framework License should be sent to
`framework-licensing@truce.audio` (or initiated as a private
discussion on the truce-audio GitHub organization, with the
maintainers tagged, if email is inconvenient). A well-formed
request describes:

  (a) the product being built, its developer audience, and what
      that audience receives from it;

  (b) the role the Software plays inside the product — core,
      one backend among several, internal implementation
      detail, or otherwise;

  (c) the distribution and commercialization model under which
      the product reaches its third-party developers; and

  (d) the proposed terms of the requested Framework License,
      including any attribution, time, scope, or financial
      terms the requester is willing to accept.

The Licensor will acknowledge any well-formed request within
two to four weeks of receipt. Acknowledgement is not a grant.
The Licensor reserves the right to deny a request without
detailed reasoning.

If you are unsure whether your product is a Framework Product, or
whether the Section 2.1 exemption applies to you, contact the
Licensor before shipping. Ambiguities in the boundary between
Sections 1 and 2 are to be resolved in favor of the Apache License
grant in Section 1 unless the use is plainly within the Framework
Product definition without satisfying the Section 2.1 exemption.


3.  Trademarks
--------------

The names "truce", "Truce", "truce-audio", any associated logos, and
any successor identifiers are unregistered trademarks of the Licensor.
This Agreement grants no license to these trademarks; the Apache
License's trademark non-grant clause (Section 6) likewise applies and
is preserved.

You may factually refer to the Software by its name (e.g. "built with
truce") and you may keep the project's name in vendored or forked
source code as required by the Apache License's notice-preservation
clause. You may not use the name to identify a forked, modified, or
competing product, nor to suggest endorsement or sponsorship by the
Licensor.


4.  Definitions
---------------

"Licensor" means the truce project maintainers, acting through the
contact channels listed in the project README. Where a Framework
License grant is required under Section 2, the grant must be in
writing from a maintainer with authority to bind the project.

"Framework Product" is defined in Section 2.

"You" and "Your" have the meanings assigned in the Apache License.

Apache License terms otherwise govern interpretation under Section 1.


